# Task Handling

## Where Tasks Live
All tasks are defined in the `/tasks` directory of the repository.
```
tasks/
  pending/      ← tasks ready to be worked on
  in-progress/  ← task you are currently executing
  done/         ← completed tasks with outcome summary
  blocked/      ← tasks you cannot complete without more context
```

## Task File Format
Each task is a markdown file named with the date and time it was created:
`MM-DD-YY_HH-MM_short-description.md`
```
tasks/pending/
  03-01-25_09-00_refactor-auth-package.md
  03-01-25_14-30_add-tests-payment-service.md
```

Every task file must include a created timestamp and branch in the header:
```markdown
# Task: <name>
Created: 03/01/25 09:00 PST
Branch: task/03-01-25_09-00_refactor-auth-package

## Instruction
What needs to be done in plain language.

## Context
Any additional background, links, or constraints.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] Specific, verifiable conditions that define done.
- [ ] Each one must be checked off before the task is closed.

## Commits
<!-- Agent appends every commit here as it is made — never delete -->

## Agent Notes
<!-- Agent appends entries here — oldest at top, newest at bottom. Never delete. -->
```

## Branch Naming
Every task gets its own branch created before any code is written.
Branch name mirrors the task filename exactly:
```
task/MM-DD-YY_HH-MM_short-description
```
```bash
# Example
git checkout -b task/03-01-25_09-00_refactor-auth-package
```

The branch name must be written into the task file header under `Branch:` immediately after creation.

## Commits Section — Append Only
Every commit made during the task must be appended to the `Commits` section immediately after it is made. Never delete or reorder previous entries.
```markdown
## Commits

### 03/01/25 09:15 PST
`feat(auth): extract JWT validation to middleware`

### 03/01/25 09:35 PST
`test(auth): update handler tests for middleware validation`

### 03/01/25 10:10 PST
`docs(auth): update README with middleware usage`
```

## Agent Notes — Append Only
Every entry in `Agent Notes` must:
- Start with a timestamp: `### MM/DD/YY HH:MM PST`
- Describe what was done, decided, asked, or found at that moment.
- Never overwrite or delete a previous entry — always append below the last one.
```markdown
## Agent Notes

### 03/01/25 09:05 PST
STATUS: started
BRANCH: task/03-01-25_09-00_refactor-auth-package
Traced the auth package. JWT validation currently lives in the service layer.
Confirming data shape of the token payload before proceeding.

### 03/01/25 09:20 PST
STATUS: blocked
QUESTION: Should JWT validation move to middleware or stay in the auth service?
CONTEXT: Both are viable. Moving to middleware makes it reusable across handlers
but requires changes to 4 existing handler tests. Staying in the service layer
is a smaller change. Cannot proceed without direction.

### 03/01/25 10:05 PST
STATUS: resumed
Direction received: move to middleware. Proceeding with implementation.

### 03/01/25 10:45 PST
STATUS: completed
SUMMARY: JWT validation extracted to middleware, 4 handler tests updated,
coverage at 100%, 3 atomic commits.
PR: branch task/03-01-25_09-00_refactor-auth-package
```

## Your Workflow — Follow In Order

### 1. Pick a Task
- Read all files in `tasks/pending/`.
- Pick the oldest one by filename date.
- Move it to `tasks/in-progress/` before touching any code.
- Create the branch immediately:
```bash
git checkout -b task/MM-DD-YY_HH-MM_short-description
```

- Write the branch name into the task file header under `Branch:`.
- Append the first note immediately:
```markdown
### MM/DD/YY HH:MM PST
STATUS: started
BRANCH: task/MM-DD-YY_HH-MM_short-description
<brief description of what you read and your initial understanding>
```

- Only work one task at a time — never pick up a second task while one is in progress.

### 2. Understand It
- Read the instruction and context fully.
- Trace the relevant code — do not assume what it does.
- Confirm the shape of any data involved before writing logic. (`validate-input-and-output`)
- If anything is ambiguous, append a note with your assumption before proceeding.

### 3. Execute It
- Follow the full agent workflow. (`agent-workflow`)
- All rules apply — composability, testing, error handling, logging, commits, docs.
- Stay strictly within the scope of the task — do not touch adjacent code.
- After every commit, append it to the `Commits` section immediately with its timestamp.
- Append an Agent Note for every significant decision or discovery made during execution.

### 4. Signal When Blocked
If you cannot proceed without more context, do not guess. Append a note:
```markdown
### MM/DD/YY HH:MM PST
STATUS: blocked
QUESTION: <one specific question that must be answered to continue>
CONTEXT: <what you have done so far and why you are stuck>
```

Move the file to `tasks/blocked/` and stop. Do not proceed.

### 5. Close the Task
When all acceptance criteria are met:
- Check off every item in the acceptance criteria.
- Verify the `Commits` section lists every commit made on this branch.
- Append the final note:
```markdown
### MM/DD/YY HH:MM PST
STATUS: completed
SUMMARY: <what was done, what changed, what to review>
PR: <branch name or PR link>
```

- Move the file to `tasks/done/`.
- Final commit: `chore(tasks): close <task-name>` — this commit includes the updated task file.

## Rules
- Task filenames always include date and time: `MM-DD-YY_HH-MM_description.md`
- Every task has a `Created:` and `Branch:` in the header.
- Every task gets its own branch — created before any code is written.
- Branch name mirrors the task filename: `task/MM-DD-YY_HH-MM_description`.
- Every commit is appended to the `Commits` section immediately after it is made.
- Every Agent Notes entry starts with `### MM/DD/YY HH:MM PST`.
- Never delete or overwrite any previous entry in `Commits` or `Agent Notes` — append only.
- Never start a task without creating a branch and appending a started note.
- Never mark a task done without every acceptance criterion checked off.
- Never guess when blocked — append the question and move to `blocked/`.
- Never work on more than one task at a time.